ve name from Clacy in the Aisne department of Picardy, France."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gérard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy, strong’. In the later Middle Ages this was a more common name than   Gerald  , with which it was sometimes confused. Nowadays it is less common, surviving mainly among Roman Catholics, in honour of the many saints of this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Gerard  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Jerrard","meanings":["Rare variant spelling of   Gerard  , probably influenced by the form of the modern surname, if not a transferred use."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gérard II de Clacy was born in 1162, his father, Hector de Clacy, was 38 and his mother, Sarrazine de Laon, was 19. He had at least 1 son with Mahaud de Quierzy. He died in 1204, in France, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1162–1204":"1162–1204","–Male":"Surnud","1165–1241":"1165–1241","1200–1247":"1200–1247","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","1143–1198":"1143–1198","1204":"1204","1247":"1247","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","1198":"1198","1143":"1143","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1162":"1162","Laon, Île-de-France, France":"Laon, Aisne, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1162–1204":"1162–1204","–Male":"Kuollut","1165–1241":"1165–1241","1200–1247":"1200–1247","1125–Male":"1125–Kuollut","1143–1198":"1143–1198","1204":"1204","1247":"1247","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","1198":"1198","1143":"1143","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","about 1200":"noin 1200","1162":"1162","Laon, Île-de-France, France":"Laon, Aisne, Picardie, Ranska","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"1162–1204":"1162–1204","–Male":"Décédé","1165–1241":"1165–1241","1200–1247":"1200–1247","1125–Male":"1125–Décédé","1143–1198":"1143–1198","1204":"1204","1247":"1247","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","1198":"1198","1143":"1143","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","about 1200":"environ 1200","1162":"1162","Laon, Île-de-Franc